    <node id="Thorp and Thig, aliens from the planet Ortha, plan to explore Earth by having Thig blend in with the inhabitants to gather information about the planet's resources and temperatures. However, Thig's behavior becomes a cause for concern when he decides to protect an Earth woman named Ellen and her children from a pernicious disease present on Planet 72-P-3.&#10;&#10;Thorpe and Thig discuss dealing with the &quot;Earthmen&quot; in the context of using one of their own kind, Thig, to blend in with the inhabitants of Earth and gather information without raising suspicion. Thig's role is crucial in this plan, but his behavior becomes a concern when he deviates from the plan by deciding to protect Ellen and her children from the potential disease on 72-P-3.&#10;&#10;Thig's behavior is a cause for concern because it shows that he has developed emotions and a sense of empathy towards the Earth woman and her children, which goes against the Orthan way of life and their single-minded devotion to the Horde. Thig's experiences on Earth have led him to question the Orthan way of life, and his decision to protect Ellen and her children could potentially jeopardize the mission and the safety of the Orthan civilization.&#10;&#10;Therefore, Thig's behavior is a cause for concern because it highlights the cultural differences between the Orthans and humans and the potential challenges that may arise from their interactions." />
    <edge source="72-P-3 is unfit for colonization due to a pernicious disease that affects the brain centers and causes violent insanity. This was discovered when Thig, who had surveyed the planet, returned and destroyed Kam, and then Torp was forced to kill Thig. Torp wrote in the ship's log that he could feel the insidious virus of the disease, but his writing ended abruptly.&#10;&#10;The Earthwoman and children traveling there are at risk of being exposed to this disease, which causes violent insanity. Torp had already shown signs of being affected before his writing ended, indicating that the disease can act quickly. Therefore, it is not safe for the Earthwoman and children to travel to 72-P-3." target=" a madman!&#10; &#10; The deadly attack of Thig; his own violent avenging of Kam's death, and now the apparent return of the man he had killed come to life had all served to jolt his rigidly trained brain from its accustomed groove. The shock had been too much for the established thought-processes of the Orthan.&#10; &#10; So Thig shot him where he stood, mercifully, before that vacant mad stare set him, too, to gibbering and shrieking. Then he stepped over the skeleton-thing that had been Torp, using the new strength that victory had given him to drive him along.&#10; &#10; He had saved a world's civilization from extinction! The thought sobered him; yet, somehow, he was pleased that he had done so. After all, it had been the Earthwoman and the children he had been thinking of while he battled Kam, a selfish desire to protect them all.&#10; &#10; He went to the desk where Torp had been writing in the ship's log and read the last few nervously scrawled lines:&#10;  Planet 72-P-3 unfit for colonization. Some pernicious disease that strikes at the brain centers and causes violent insanity is existent there.">
