ssed firsthand the rapid onset and devastating effects of the pernicious disease present on 72-P-3. He may question whether it is necessary to destroy all biped life on the planet, rather than finding a way to contain or cure the disease.&#10;&#10;Finally, Thig's decision to cut free an auxiliary lifeboat and set a course for Ortha suggests that he values individual autonomy and agency. He may question whether it is right for Torp to make a unilateral decision to destroy all biped life on 72-P-3 without considering alternative perspectives or approaches.&#10;&#10;Overall, while the story does not explicitly provide information about Thig questioning Torp's decision, it is possible to infer that his character development and experiences on Earth may lead him to question the morality and necessity of the Horde's usual approach to colonization.">
