    <edge source="The Orthan, a member of an advanced alien race called the Hordes of Ortha, initially questions the value of the Hordes' sole devotion to their civilization at the expense of all other interests. He wonders what good it would do to populate new worlds with more of the same, as he sees it. However, his perspective gets challenged by his emotional experiences and interactions with humans during his time on Earth.&#10;&#10;Firstly, Thig (the Orthan) develops a sense of sentimentality towards Earth's beauty, such as when he recalls the Grand Canyon and mornings in the desert. He also forms an emotional bond with a human woman named Ellen and her sick child, showing compassion and care for them.&#10;&#10;Thig's experiences on Earth open his mind to new ways of thinking and feeling, making him question the Horde's relentless pursuit of growth and power over all else. As he starts empathizing with humans, Thig grapples with the idea of eliminating an entire species for the sake of the Horde's expansion. His growing individualism and self-awareness lead him to challenge the very foundations of the Horde's culture and values.&#10;&#10;In summary, the Orthan's perspective on the Hordes' devotion to their civilization changes as he experiences emotions and human connections that conflict with his people's single-minded focus on growth and power. This emotional journey raises questions about the morality of the Horde's expansionist goals and highlights the value of individuality, empathy, and compassion." target="1. The Orthan, Thig, initially perceives human civilization as stagnant, likely due to the Hordes of Ortha's emphasis on constant growth and expansion. However, as he spends more time on Earth, he begins to appreciate its beauty, forms emotional bonds with humans, and develops empathy for their lives. This contrasts sharply with the Horde's collective goals and leads Thig to challenge his previous perspective on humanity's stagnation.&#10;&#10;Reference(s):&#10;Thig's interactions with the human woman Ellen and her sick child, as well as his emotional experiences of Earth's beauty, contribute to this shift in perspective. These personal experiences help him see individuality, empathy, and compassion as valuable aspects of civilization.&#10;&#10;The story suggests that Thig's growing appreciation for human culture makes him question the Horde's relentless pursuit of growth and power. His emotional journey raises questions about the morality of the Horde's expansionist goals and highlights the value of individuality, empathy, and compassion. This internal conflict indicates a significant change in Thig's perspective on humanity's &quot;stagnation.&quot;&#10;&#10;In summary, the Orthan's perspective on human civilization evolves as he develops emotional connections and forms a newfound appreciation for individuality, empathy, and compassion. These experiences challenge his original view of humanity as stagnant, highlighting the importance of personal growth and understanding in cross-cultural interactions.">
