    <edge source=" nothing must stand between them! The Hordes of Ortha must find some other world, an empty worldâ€”this planet was not for them.&#10; &#10; &quot;Turn back!&quot; he cried wildly. &quot;I must go back to Earth. There is a woman there, helpless and alone, who needs me! The Horde does not need this planet.&quot;&#10; &#10; Kam eyed him coldly and lifted a shining hypodermic syringe from its case. He approached Thig warily, aware that disease often made a maniac of the finest members of the Horde.&#10; &#10; &quot;No human being is more important than the Horde,&quot; he stated baldly.&#10;&quot;This woman of whom you speak is merely one unit of the millions we must eliminate for the good of the Horde.&quot;&#10; &#10; Then it was that Thig went berserk. His fists slashed into the thick jaw of the scientist and his fingers ripped at the hard cords overlying the Orthan's vital throat tubes. His fingers and thumb gouged deep into Kam's startled throat and choked off any cry for assistance before it could be uttered.&#10; &#10; Kam's hand swept down to the holster swung from his intricate harness and dragged his blaster from it. Thig's other hand clamped over" target="Thig goes berserk when Kam dismisses the importance of an individual human life compared to the Horde because he has developed a sense of empathy and concern for Ellen and her children, which contrasts with the Horde's usual approach of valuing order and efficiency over individual lives. This emotional connection to humanity, particularly Ellen and her children, drives Thig to prioritize their safety and well-being, leading him to question the morality of destroying an entire planet's biped life.&#10;&#10;Furthermore, Thig has witnessed firsthand the rapid onset and devastating effects of the pernicious disease present on 72-P-3. This experience may have made him more cautious about resorting to extreme measures like exterminating all biped life on the planet without considering alternative