    <edge source="1. Thig's initial purpose on Earth is to explore and assess the planet's suitability for colonization by his people, the Hordes of Ortha. However, after witnessing a violent episode involving himself, Kam, and Torp, as well as observing the power of the decomposition blaster and the ship's departure from the planet, Thig feels an urgent need to protect Ellen (the Earthwoman) and her children from this potential disease. As a result, he decides to cut free an auxiliary lifeboat and set a course for Ortha, knowing that Torp's body will help confirm his final message about the danger on 72-P-3." target="Thig and Torp's encounter results in both of them being injured. Thig has collapsed on his face while crawling towards the door with a blaster, and Torp is described as a &quot;crumpled blood-smeared heap of bruised flesh and bone&quot; in the corner of the laboratory. Thig shoots Torp &quot;mercifully,&quot; suggesting that Torp is still alive at this point but possibly critically injured.&#10;&#10;Thig's aggressive behavior towards Torp was triggered by a combination of factors. First, seeing the cases of fragile instruments above his head reminded him of the heavy blaster in its rack beneath them, leading him to feel the weapon and tug it free. Second, while crawling towards the door with the blaster, Thig collapsed on his face, causing Torp to cry out in surprise, which likely added to his confusion and madness. Finally, Thig's rigidly trained brain had been shocked by the sight of his commander, a man he had killed and who was now apparently alive again, combined with the thought of protecting Ellen and the children, leading him to shoot Torp &quot;mercifully.&quot;&#10;&#10;Therefore, it was a combination of Thig's suspicion towards Torp, his own violent avenging of Kam's death, and the shock of seeing the man he had killed come back to life that triggered his attempt to attack Torp.">
