    <edge source=" against his new body was strangely exhilerating and heady. It was the newest of the emotions he had experienced on Earth since that day, so many months before, when he had felt the warmness of Ellen's lips tight against his.&#10; &#10; &#10; Thig flipped the drive lever, felt the thrumming of the rockets driving him from the parent ship.&#10; &#10;&#10; &#10; He swung about to the port, watched the flaming drive-rockets of the great exploratory ship hurl it toward far-away Ortha, and there was no regret in his mind that he was not returning to the planet of his first existence.&#10; &#10; He thought of the dull greys and blacks of his planet, of the monotonous routine of existence that had once been hisâ€”and his heart thrilled to the memories of the starry nights and perfect exciting days he had spent on his three month trip over Earth.&#10; &#10; He made a brief salute to the existence he had known, turned with a tiny sigh, and his fingers made brief adjustments in the controls. The rocket-thrum deepened, and the thin whistle of tenuous air clutching the ship echoed through the hull-plates.&#10; &#10; He thought of many things in those" target="The space alien, named Thig who is also the alter ego of the human writer Lewis Terry, is experiencing a range of complex emotions as he allows himself to be pulled towards Earth. He feels a deep sense of nostalgia and sentimentality towards Earth's beauty, recalling the Grand Canyon and mornings in the desert. Thig has developed an emotional bond with a human woman named Ellen and her sick child, showing compassion and care for them, which is a new experience for him.&#10;&#10;Despite having acquired human traits and memory, Thig still grapples with his alienness and feels like an outsider. He shivers at the memory of his callousness in sending space ships hurtling towards the hills and valleys below and feels sick at the realization that he is an alien from outer space. He fingers the tiny scars that have obliterated the slight differences in his appearance from an Earthman's, and his fingers tremble as he stares through the vision port. Thig says a brief prayer in his heart to a God whose presence he now feels very deeply, indicating a deep sense of spiritual connection and reverence.&#10;&#10;Thus, Thig is experiencing a range of human emotions such as nostalgia, compassion, and spiritual connection, while also grappling with his alienness and the implications of his existence for his people, the Hordes of Ortha. This emotional journey raises questions about the morality of the Horde's expansionist goals and highlights the value of individuality, empathy, and compassion.">
