    <edge source="According to the story, Torp, a commander from Ortha, plans to explore Earth by using one of their kind to blend in with the inhabitants of Earth. They have a device that can transfer memories and knowledge to one of their own, allowing them to disguise themselves as an Earthman. Thig, who is emotionless and robot-like, is chosen for this task. He is to scout the planet without raising suspicion while Torp and Kam explore the inner planets. Thig's role is to gather information about Earth's resources and temperatures, which he has done and reported back to Torp.&#10;&#10;However, Thig has developed a desire to protect Ellen (an Earth woman) and her children from a potential disease that he witnessed on Earth. To do this, Thig cuts free an auxiliary lifeboat and sets a course for Ortha, taking Terry's body with him. Thig hopes that the Earthman's memories and knowledge will help confirm his final message about the danger on 72-P-3.&#10;&#10;In summary, Torp's plan to explore Earth involves using one of their own kind, Thig, to blend in with the inhabitants of Earth and gather information. Thig plays a crucial role in this plan by gathering information about Earth's resources and temperatures, but he ultimately deviates from the plan by deciding to protect Ellen and her children from the potential disease on 72-P-3." target="The struggle between Kam and Thig results in Kam being killed by his own decomposition blaster, which was triggered by Thig. The weapon causes half of Kam's body to &quot;slough away into foul corruption&quot; before turning into hardened blobs of dessicated matter. This event is emotionally devastating for Thig, who had developed a desire to protect Ellen and her children from the potential disease that he witnessed on Earth. Seeing his own comrade become affected by the disease and turn violent has made Thig realize the danger it poses, leading him to take drastic measures to ensure the safety of Ellen and her children. The emotional impact of this event on Thig is not explicitly stated in the story, but it can be inferred that he experiences horror, guilt, and a sense of urgency to protect others from the disease.">
